  "prompt": "Which machine learning book is best for a beginner who intends to do research in reinforcement learning later?",
  "response": "For a beginner who intends to do research in reinforcement learning later, a good starting point would be \"Hands-On Machine Learning with Scikit-Learn, Keras, and TensorFlow\" by Aur\u00e9lien G\u00e9ron. This book provides a practical introduction to machine learning concepts and tools, and it's very accessible to beginners. \n\nOnce you have a good grasp of the basics from that book, you can move on to more specialized reinforcement learning books. \"Reinforcement Learning: An Introduction\" by Richard S. Sutton and Andrew G. Barto is regarded as the seminal textbook for reinforcement learning. It offers an in-depth look at the core concepts and algorithms in the field and is highly recommended for anyone looking to conduct research in this area.\n\nCombining these two resources will provide a solid foundation in general machine learning, followed by a deep dive into reinforcement learning, well-suited for research purposes.",
